 .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lynn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhloinn</b> and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn  ).","Scottish: variant of   Lyne   3.","English: habitational name from any of several places so called in Norfolk, in particular King's Lynn, an important center of the medieval wool trade. The placename is probably from an Old Welsh word cognate with Gaelic <i>linn</i> ‘pool, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lyn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Ding, Fatt, Tov, Yol, Yun.","Scottish and English: variant of   Lynn  .","Probably also an altered form of Dutch <b>Van der Lijn</b> (see   Vanderlinden  )."]},{"name":"Linn","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","German: habitational name from a place called Linn, named with <i>lin</i> ‘swamp, bog, marsh’.","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Linto</i>, formed with Old High German <i>lind(i)</i> ‘soft’."]},{"name":"Lenn","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","Jewish(Ashkenazic): variant of   Len  ."]},{"name":"Flynn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Connor, Declan, Kieran, Aidan, Brigid, Cathal, Dermot, Donal, Eamon, John Patrick, Kiernan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Floinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Flann</i>’, a byname meaning ‘red(dish), ruddy’. There were families of this name in various parts of Ireland. This name has also been Anglicized as   Lindsay  .","English: from Middle English <i>Flin</i>, representing the Old Norse male personal name <i>Fleinn</i>."]},{"name":"Lynne","meanings":["Scottish or English: variant of   Lynn  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of Fi